---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">GSE vs. LMC: reshaping of radially biased stellar haloes by satellites</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Dillamore et al. (2026)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Type:</th>
          <td>Paper</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Authors:</th>
          <td>Adam M. Dillamore, Jason L. Sanders, Richard A. N. Brooks</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>arXiv / DOI:</th>
          <td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11159">arXiv:2603.11159</a> — <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2603.11159">DOI</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Date:</th>
          <td>2026-03-11 (v1) — MNRAS submitted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Analysis:</th>
          <td><a href="/data/papers/dillamore2026_gse_lmc_halo_perturbation.md">Paper analysis (markdown)</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Related concepts:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/gaia_sausage_enceladus" text="Gaia Sausage-Enceladus" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/lmc_perturbations" text="LMC perturbations" />
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Abstract (short)</strong> — Dillamore et al. show that LMC perturbations can reshape the MW's stellar halo from axisymmetric to triaxial and tilted configurations. Using test-particle simulations with varying velocity anisotropy (β ∈ [0.5, 0.9]), they demonstrate that highly eccentric orbits (e ≳ 0.95) preferentially align with the LMC's tidal field on ~1 Gyr timescales, creating overdensities that coincide with the Virgo Overdensity and Hercules-Aquila Cloud.</p>

    <h2 id="key-findings">Key findings</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        The LMC causes initially axisymmetric haloes to become triaxial; major axes tilt by ~14° out of the Galactic plane.  
        <small><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11159">(Dillamore et al. 2026, arXiv:2603.11159)</a></small>
      </li>
      <li>
        Orbits with high eccentricity (e ≳ 0.95) undergo azimuthal alignment with the LMC's tidal field on ~1 Gyr timescales, as predicted by an analytical pendulum-like model.  
        <small>(Dillamore+2026)</small>
      </li>
      <li>
        The halo fractionates by anisotropy: the highly radial β = 0.9 component preferentially concentrates into Virgo Overdensity and Hercules-Aquila Cloud overdensities (~40% excess density).  
        <small>(Dillamore+2026)</small>
      </li>
      <li>
        HAC and VOD may originate from LMC-driven orbital alignment, not GSE merger geometry; this reframes the need for a tilted dark matter halo in equilibrium models.  
        <small>(Dillamore+2026)</small>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="methods">Methods</h2>
    <p>The authors combine analytical theory (pendulum dynamics in a tidal field) with test-particle simulations. They build Schwarzschild orbit-superposition models of haloes with different anisotropies (β = 0.5–0.9), evolve them forward in a realistic Milky Way potential including the LMC's 3.9 Gyr infall history, and measure halo shape via inertia tensor analysis. The LMC is modeled as a rigid NFW potential with Chandrasekhar dynamical friction.</p>

    <h2 id="implications">Implications</h2>
    <p>
      LMC perturbations must be corrected for when constructing equilibrium models of the inner Milky Way halo. The observed tilt and triaxiality of the GSE/halo may not require a long-lived tilted dark matter halo; the LMC + high-β stars suffice. HAC and VOD may have dynamical rather than merger-origin interpretations, reshaping our understanding of halo structure formation.
    </p>

